&lt;p&gt;ÐÐ¾ Ð²ÑÐµÐ¼Ñ Ð±ÐµÑÐµÐ´Ñ ÐÐ¾Ð½Ð°ÑÐ¸Ð½Ñ ÑÐ°ÑÑÐºÐ°Ð·Ð°Ð»Ð°, ÐºÐ°Ðº ÐµÐ¹ ÑÐ´Ð°Ð»Ð¾ÑÑ ÑÐ¿Ð°ÑÑÐ¸ Ð´Ð²Ð° Ð´ÐµÑÑÑÐºÐ° Ð¶ÐµÐ½ÑÐ¸Ð½ Ð¾Ñ ÑÑÑÑÐ¼Ñ. ÐÐ½Ð¸ Ð¿Ð¾Ð¿Ð°Ð»Ð¸ ÑÑÐ´Ð° Ð·Ð° Ð½ÐµÐ·Ð°ÐºÐ¾Ð½Ð½ÑÑ Ð´ÐµÑÑÐµÐ»ÑÐ½Ð¾ÑÑÑ Ð¸Ð·-Ð·Ð° Ð±ÐµÐ´Ð½Ð¾ÑÑÐ¸ Ð¸ Ð³Ð¾ÑÑÑÐ¾ ÑÐ°ÑÐºÐ°Ð¸Ð²Ð°Ð»Ð¸ÑÑ Ð² ÑÐ²Ð¾Ð¸Ñ Ð¿Ð¾ÑÑÑÐ¿ÐºÐ°Ñ. ÐÐ°ÑÑ Ð¢ÐµÑÐµÐ·Ð° Ð·Ð°Ð²ÐµÑÐ¸Ð»Ð° ÑÑÐºÐ¾Ð²Ð¾Ð´ÑÑÐ²Ð¾ ÐºÐ°Ð»ÑÐºÑÑÑÑÐºÐ¾Ð¹ ÑÑÑÑÐ¼Ñ, ÑÑÐ¾ Ð±ÐµÑÐµÑ Ð½Ð° ÑÐµÐ±Ñ Ð¾ÑÐ²ÐµÑÑÑÐ²ÐµÐ½Ð½Ð¾ÑÑÑ Ð·Ð° Ð¸Ñ Ð¶Ð¸Ð·Ð½Ð¸. ÐÑÐµ ÑÑÐ¸ Ð¶ÐµÐ½ÑÐ¸Ð½Ñ Ð² ÐºÐ¾Ð½ÐµÑÐ½Ð¾Ð¼ Ð¸ÑÐ¾Ð³Ðµ ÑÑÐ°Ð»Ð¸ Ð¼Ð¾Ð½Ð°ÑÐ¸Ð½ÑÐ¼Ð¸, ÑÐµÑÑÑÐ°Ð¼Ð¸ ÐµÐµ ÐÐ¸ÑÑÐ¸Ð¸ Ð¼Ð¸Ð»Ð¾ÑÐµÑÐ´Ð¸Ñ. ÐÐ°ÐºÐ¾Ð½ÑÐ¸Ð² ÑÐ²Ð¾Ð¹ ÑÐ°ÑÑÐºÐ°Ð·, Ð¾Ð½Ð° Ð¿ÑÐ¸Ð±Ð°Ð²Ð¸Ð»Ð°: &amp;laquo;ÐÐ¾Ñ ÑÑÐ¾ Ð¼Ð¾Ð¶ÐµÑ ÑÐ´ÐµÐ»Ð°ÑÑ Ð»ÑÐ±Ð¾Ð²Ñ. ÐÐ¸ÑÑ Ð½ÑÐ¶Ð½Ð° Ð»Ð¸ÑÑ Ð»ÑÐ±Ð¾Ð²Ñ, Ð»ÑÐ±Ð¾Ð²Ñ, Ð»ÑÐ±Ð¾Ð²Ñ&amp;raquo;. Ð¡Ð²ÑÑÐ°Ñ Ð´Ð°Ð»Ð° Ð¸Ð¼ ÑÑÐ¾Ð»ÑÐºÐ¾ Ð½ÐµÐ¶Ð½Ð¾ÑÑÐ¸, ÑÑÐ¾ Ð¾Ð½Ð¸ Ð² ÐºÐ¾Ð½ÐµÑÐ½Ð¾Ð¼ Ð¸ÑÐ¾Ð³Ðµ Ð¿ÑÐ¸ÑÐ¾ÐµÐ´Ð¸Ð½Ð¸Ð»Ð¸ÑÑ Ðº ÐµÐµ ÐÑÐ´ÐµÐ½Ñ. Ð¢Ð°Ðº Ð¿ÑÐ¾Ð¸ÑÑÐ¾Ð´Ð¸Ð»Ð¾ Ð½Ðµ ÑÐ°Ð· &amp;mdash; ÐÐ°ÑÑ Ð¢ÐµÑÐµÐ·Ð° Ð¾ÑÐ²Ð¾Ð±Ð¾Ð¶Ð´Ð°Ð»Ð° Ð³Ð¾ÑÐµÐ¼ÑÑÐ½ÑÑ Ð¸ Ð¸Ð·Ð¼ÐµÐ½ÑÐ»Ð° Ð¸Ñ Ð¶Ð¸Ð·Ð½Ð¸.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Ð ÐºÐ½Ð¸Ð³Ñ Ð²ÐºÐ»ÑÑÐµÐ½Ñ ÑÑÐµÐ½Ñ Ð¸Ð· Ð¿ÑÐµÑÑ &amp;laquo;Ð¡ÑÐ½&amp;raquo; Ð¾ Ð¥ÑÐ¸ÑÑÐµ Ð¡Ð¿Ð°ÑÐ¸ÑÐµÐ»Ðµ; ÑÐµÐºÑÑÑ Ð¿ÐµÑÐµÐ½, Ð½Ð°Ð¿Ð¸ÑÐ°Ð½Ð½ÑÑ Ð² ÑÐµÑÑÑ ÐÐ°ÑÐµÑÐ¸ Ð¢ÐµÑÐµÐ·Ñ, ÐºÐ¾ÑÐ¾ÑÑÐµ Ð¸ÑÐ¿Ð¾Ð»Ð½ÑÐ»Ð¸ÑÑ Ð²Ð¾ Ð²ÑÐµÐ¼Ñ Ð²ÑÑÑÐµÐ½Ð¸Ñ ÐµÐ¹ Ð½Ð°Ð³ÑÐ°Ð´Ñ ÐÐ¸ÑÐ° Ð¸Ð¼ÐµÐ½Ð¸ Ð£ Ð¢Ð°Ð½Ð° Ð² 1994 Ð³Ð¾Ð´Ñ. Ð¨ÑÐ¸ Ð§Ð¸Ð½Ð¼Ð¾Ð¹ ÑÐ°ÐºÐ¶Ðµ Ð¿Ð¾Ð»Ð¾Ð¶Ð¸Ð» Ð½Ð° Ð¼ÑÐ·ÑÐºÑ Ð¿ÑÐµÐ¸ÑÐ¿Ð¾Ð»Ð½ÐµÐ½Ð½ÑÐµ ÐÑÐµÐ²ÑÑÐ½ÐµÐ¹ Ð¼ÑÐ´ÑÐ¾ÑÑÐ¸ Ð¼Ð¾Ð»Ð¸ÑÐ²Ñ ÐÐ°ÑÐµÑÐ¸ Ð¢ÐµÑÐµÐ·Ñ Ð¸ ÐÐ¸Ð±Ð»ÐµÐ¹ÑÐºÐ¸Ðµ Ð·Ð°Ð¿Ð¾Ð²ÐµÐ´Ð¸.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;ÐÐ¾ Ð²ÑÐµÐ¼Ñ Ð²ÑÑÑÐµÑ Ñ ÐÐ°ÑÐµÑÑÑ Ð¢ÐµÑÐµÐ·Ð¾Ð¹ Ð¨ÑÐ¸ Ð§Ð¸Ð½Ð¼Ð¾Ð¹ Ð¿ÐµÑÐµÐ´Ð°Ð²Ð°Ð» Ð´Ð»Ñ ÐÐ¸ÑÑÐ¸Ð¸ Ð¼Ð¸Ð»Ð¾ÑÐµÑÐ´Ð¸Ñ Ð´ÐµÐ½ÐµÐ¶Ð½ÑÐµ ÑÑÐµÐ´ÑÑÐ²Ð°, Ð¼ÐµÐ´Ð¸ÐºÐ°Ð¼ÐµÐ½ÑÑ Ð¸ Ð½ÐµÐ¾Ð±ÑÐ¾Ð´Ð¸Ð¼Ð¾Ðµ Ð¼ÐµÐ´Ð¸ÑÐ¸Ð½ÑÐºÐ¾Ðµ Ð¾Ð±Ð¾ÑÑÐ´Ð¾Ð²Ð°Ð½Ð¸Ðµ, ÐºÐ¾ÑÐ¾ÑÐ¾Ðµ ÐµÐ³Ð¾ ÑÑÐµÐ½Ð¸ÐºÐ¸ Ð´Ð¾ÑÑÐ°Ð²Ð»ÑÐ»Ð¸ Ð¸Ð· ÑÐ°Ð·Ð½ÑÑ ÑÑÑÐ°Ð½. ÐÑÑÐ°Ð¶Ð°Ñ Ð±Ð»Ð°Ð³Ð¾Ð´Ð°ÑÐ½Ð¾ÑÑÑ Ð·Ð° Ð¿Ð¾Ð´Ð´ÐµÑÐ¶ÐºÑ ÐµÐµ Ð´ÐµÑÑÐµÐ»ÑÐ½Ð¾ÑÑÐ¸, Ð¡Ð²ÑÑÐ°Ñ Ð¾ÑÐ¼ÐµÑÐ¸Ð»Ð°: &amp;laquo;ÐÐ°Ð¶Ð½Ð¾ Ð½Ðµ ÑÐ¾, ÑÑÐ¾ Ð¼Ñ Ð´ÐµÐ»Ð°ÐµÐ¼, Ð° ÑÐ¾, ÑÐºÐ¾Ð»ÑÐºÐ¾ Ð»ÑÐ±Ð²Ð¸ Ð² Ð½Ð°ÑÐ¸Ñ ÑÐµÑÐ´ÑÐ°Ñ. ÐÐ¾Ð¼Ð½Ð¸ÑÐµ, ÑÐ»Ð¾Ð²Ð° Ð»ÑÐ±Ð²Ð¸ &amp;mdash; ÑÑÐ¾ ÑÐ»Ð¾Ð²Ð° Ð¼Ð¸ÑÐ°&amp;raquo;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;ÐÐ°Ð¶Ð´ÑÐ¹ ÑÐ°Ð·, Ð´Ð°Ð¶Ðµ Ð²Ð¾ Ð²ÑÐµÐ¼Ñ Ð¿Ð¾ÑÐ»ÐµÐ´Ð½ÐµÐ³Ð¾ ÑÐµÐ»ÐµÑÐ¾Ð½Ð½Ð¾Ð³Ð¾ ÑÐ°Ð·Ð³Ð¾Ð²Ð¾ÑÐ°, ÐºÐ¾ÑÐ¾ÑÑÐ¹ ÑÐ¾ÑÑÐ¾ÑÐ»ÑÑ Ð·Ð° Ð´ÐµÐ²ÑÑÑ Ð´Ð½ÐµÐ¹ Ð´Ð¾ ÐµÐµ ÑÐ¼ÐµÑÑÐ¸, ÐÐ¾Ð½Ð°ÑÐ¸Ð½Ñ Ð¿ÑÐ¾ÑÐ¸Ð»Ð° Ð´ÑÑÐ¾Ð²Ð½Ð¾Ð³Ð¾ Ð£ÑÐ¸ÑÐµÐ»Ñ Ð¼Ð¾Ð»Ð¸ÑÑÑÑ Ð·Ð° Ð½ÐµÐµ Ð¸ ÐµÐµ Ð´ÐµÐ»Ð¾. Ð ÑÐ²Ð¾Ñ Ð¾ÑÐµÑÐµÐ´Ñ Ð¾Ð½Ð° Ð¸ÑÐºÑÐµÐ½Ð½Ðµ Ð¼Ð¾Ð»Ð¸Ð»Ð°ÑÑ Ð·Ð° Ð½ÐµÐ³Ð¾ Ð¸ Ð±Ð»Ð°Ð³Ð¾ÑÐ»Ð¾Ð²Ð¸Ð»Ð° ÑÐ°ÐºÐµÐ» Ð¼Ð¸ÑÐ° &amp;laquo;ÐÑÐµÐ¼Ð¸ÑÐ½Ð¾Ð³Ð¾ ÐÐµÐ³Ð° ÐÐ°ÑÐ¼Ð¾Ð½Ð¸Ð¸&amp;raquo;, Ð¾ÑÐ³Ð°Ð½Ð¸Ð·Ð¾Ð²Ð°Ð½Ð½Ð¾Ð³Ð¾ Ð¨ÑÐ¸ Ð§Ð¸Ð½Ð¼Ð¾ÐµÐ¼.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;ÐÐ½Ð¸Ð³Ð° &amp;laquo;ÐÐ°ÑÑ Ð¢ÐµÑÐµÐ·Ð°: Ð¦Ð²ÐµÑÐ¾Ðº-Ð¡ÐµÑÐ´ÑÐµ ÑÐµÐ»Ð¾Ð²ÐµÑÐµÑÑÐ²Ð°, ÐÑÐ¾Ð¼Ð°Ñ-ÐÑÑÐ° ÐÐ¾Ð¶ÐµÑÑÐ²ÐµÐ½Ð½Ð¾ÑÑÐ¸&amp;raquo; Ð½Ð°Ð¿Ð¾Ð»Ð½ÐµÐ½Ð° Ð±ÐµÐ·Ð³ÑÐ°Ð½Ð¸ÑÐ½Ð¾Ð¹ Ð»ÑÐ±Ð¾Ð²ÑÑ Ð¸ Ð½ÐµÐ¶Ð½Ð¾ÑÑÑÑ Ðº Ð¡Ð²ÑÑÐ¾Ð¹. ÐÐ¾ ÑÐ°Ð¼Ð¾Ðµ Ð³Ð»Ð°Ð²Ð½Ð¾Ðµ &amp;mdash; ÑÐ¾, ÑÑÐ¾ ÑÑÐ¾Ð³Ð°ÑÐµÐ»ÑÐ½ÑÐµ Ð¿Ð¾Ð´ÑÐ¾Ð±Ð½Ð¾ÑÑÐ¸ Ð¾Ð±ÑÐµÐ½Ð¸Ñ Ð´Ð²ÑÑ Ð½ÐµÐ¾ÑÐ´Ð¸Ð½Ð°ÑÐ½ÑÑ Ð»Ð¸ÑÐ½Ð¾ÑÑÐµÐ¹, ÑÑÑ Ð¶Ð¸Ð·Ð½Ñ Ð±ÑÐ»Ð° ÐÑÐµÐ²ÑÑÐ½Ð¸Ð¼ Ð¿ÑÐ¸Ð·Ð²Ð°Ð½Ð¸ÐµÐ¼ ÑÐ°Ð¼Ð¾Ð¾ÑÐ²ÐµÑÐ¶ÐµÐ½Ð½Ð¾Ð³Ð¾ ÑÐ»ÑÐ¶ÐµÐ½Ð¸Ñ Ð»ÑÐ´ÑÐ¼, Ð½Ð°Ð¿Ð¾Ð¼Ð¸Ð½Ð°ÑÑ Ð½Ð°Ð¼ Ð¾ Ð½Ð°ÑÑÐ¾ÑÑÐ¸Ñ Ð´ÑÑÐ¾Ð²Ð½ÑÑ ÑÐµÐ½Ð½Ð¾ÑÑÑÑ Ð¸ Ð²Ð´Ð¾ÑÐ½Ð¾Ð²Ð»ÑÑÑ ÑÐ»ÑÐ¶Ð¸ÑÑ Ð±Ð¾Ð¶ÐµÑÑÐ²ÐµÐ½Ð½Ð¾Ð¼Ñ Ð² ÑÐµÐ±Ðµ, Ð¸ ÐºÐ°Ðº ÑÐ»ÐµÐ´ÑÑÐ²Ð¸Ðµ &amp;mdash; Ð² Ð´ÑÑÐ³Ð¸Ñ.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;ÐÐ°ÑÑ Ð¢ÐµÑÐµÐ·Ð° Ð½Ðµ Ð½ÑÐ¶Ð´Ð°ÐµÑÑÑ Ð² Ð½Ð°ÑÐ¸Ñ Ð¿Ð¾ÑÐµÑÑÑÑ, Ð¾Ð´Ð½Ð°ÐºÐ¾, ÑÐµÑÑÐ²ÑÑ ÐµÐµ, Ð¼Ñ Ð¿ÑÐ¸ÑÐ¼Ð½Ð¾Ð¶Ð°ÐµÐ¼ ÑÐ²Ð¾Ðµ ÑÐ¾Ð±ÑÑÐ²ÐµÐ½Ð½Ð¾Ðµ Ð²Ð´Ð¾ÑÐ½Ð¾Ð²ÐµÐ½Ð¸Ðµ Ð¸ ÑÑÑÐµÐ¼Ð»ÐµÐ½Ð¸Ðµ ÑÑÐ°ÑÑ Ð»ÑÑÑÐ¸Ð¼Ð¸ Ð³ÑÐ°Ð¶Ð´Ð°Ð½Ð°Ð¼Ð¸ Ð¼Ð¸ÑÐ°. ÐÑÑÐ°Ð¶Ð°Ñ ÑÐ²Ð°Ð¶ÐµÐ½Ð¸Ðµ, Ð²Ð¾ÑÑÐ¸ÑÐµÐ½Ð¸Ðµ Ð¸ Ð¿Ð¾ÑÑÐµÐ½Ð¸Ðµ Ð´ÑÑÐ³Ð¾Ð¼Ñ ÑÐµÐ»Ð¾Ð²ÐµÐºÑ, Ð¼Ñ Ð¿ÑÐ¸ÑÐ¼Ð½Ð¾Ð¶Ð°ÐµÐ¼ ÑÐ²Ð¾Ð¸ ÑÐ¿Ð¾ÑÐ¾Ð±Ð½Ð¾ÑÑÐ¸ Ð¸ Ð²ÑÐ²Ð¾Ð´Ð¸Ð¼ Ð½Ð° Ð¿ÐµÑÐµÐ´Ð½Ð¸Ð¹ Ð¿Ð»Ð°Ð½ ÑÐ²Ð¾Ð¹ ÑÐ¾Ð±ÑÑÐ²ÐµÐ½Ð½ÑÐ¹ Ð±Ð¾Ð¶ÐµÑÑÐ²ÐµÐ½Ð½ÑÐ¹ Ð¿Ð¾ÑÐµÐ½ÑÐ¸Ð°Ð». Ð¡Ð¾ ÑÐ»Ð¾Ð² Ð¨ÑÐ¸ Ð§Ð¸Ð½Ð¼Ð¾Ñ:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;laquo;ÐÐ°ÑÑ Ð¢ÐµÑÐµÐ·Ð° Ð¿Ð¾ÐºÐ°Ð·ÑÐ²Ð°ÐµÑ Ð½Ð°Ð¼, ÐºÐ°Ðº ÑÐ¸Ð»Ð¾Ð¹ Ð¸ÑÐºÑÐµÐ½Ð½Ð¸Ñ Ð¼Ð¾Ð»Ð¸ÑÐ²&lt;br /&gt;
	ÐÑ Ð¼Ð¾Ð¶ÐµÐ¼ Ð¿Ð¾Ð´Ð½ÑÑÑ ÑÐ²Ð¾Ñ ÑÐºÐ¾ÑÐ±Ð½ÑÑ Ð²Ð½ÐµÑÐ½ÑÑ Ð¶Ð¸Ð·Ð½Ñ&lt;br /&gt;
	Ð Ð²ÑÑÐ¾ÑÐµ ÑÐ¾Ð±ÑÑÐ²ÐµÐ½Ð½Ð¾Ð³Ð¾ Ð²Ð½ÑÑÑÐµÐ½Ð½ÐµÐ³Ð¾ ÑÐ²ÐµÑÐ°&amp;raquo;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;ÐÐ°ÑÐ¸Ñ ÐÐÐÐ§Ð£Ð&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;30.11.2012&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.day.kiev.ua/ru/article/pochta-dnya/vsevyshnee-prizvanie&quot;&gt;ÐÐ¶ÐµÐ´Ð½ÐµÐ²Ð½Ð°Ñ Ð²ÑÐµÑÐºÑÐ°Ð¸Ð½ÑÐºÐ°Ñ Ð³Ð°Ð·ÐµÑÐ° &amp;quot;ÐÐµÐ½Ñ&amp;quot;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;


    

    &lt;span class=&quot;country&quot; x-autocompletetype=&quot;country&quot; autocomplete=&quot;country&quot;&gt;Russia&lt;/span&gt;    

    &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.srichinmoycentre.org/category/interests/writing&quot;&gt;Writing &amp;amp; Poetry&lt;/a&gt;    

    Normal page    

    POINT (105.318756 61.52401)    

    Add page to category map    
&lt;div class=&quot;field-collection-container clearfix&quot;&gt;
    
&lt;/div&gt;</description>
 <pubDate>Mon, 03 Dec 2012 05:18:10 +0000</pubDate>
 <dc:creator>Lotika</dc:creator>
 <guid isPermaLink="false">12880 at http://www.srichinmoycentre.org</guid>
</item>
<item>
 <title>Inspiration Letters 26</title>
 <link>http://www.srichinmoycentre.org/inspiration-letters-26</link>
 <description>
    &lt;p&gt;&lt;img alt=&quot; Luminaries Edition&quot; class=&quot;right&quot; src=&quot;http://aum.vasudevaserver.netdna-cdn.com/cdn/farfuture/nSE70Hvrn418RvSvHZYTbNFyRv1_517a2T0OK_nwG3g/mtime:1350865117/files/inspiration-letters/images/26/running-edition.jpg&quot; style=&quot;width:350px; height:610px&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Running is sometimes really difficult for me. I get shin splints very easily, and often my knees ache. But, nothing gives me the kind of exhilaration, the sense of limitless freedom, that running does. I think Sri Chinmoy said somewhere that, when we run, each breath we take is connected with a kind of higher reality. He said that running connects our breath with a higher, spiritual breath, and that divine breath is like a blessing for our entire physical body. (You can find his discussion of this phenomenon &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.srichinmoylibrary.com/books/1427/1/12/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When I turned thirty, I got up early in the morning and did hill work on the big steep hill on 150th street between Hillside Avenue and the Grand Central Parkway. Trust me, it is an unbelievably steep and difficult hill! As I was running up and down the hill, I saw a frail old man, very nicely dressed, walking up the hill. He was a little bent over, almost crooked, and was obviously moving with difficulty. The fourth or fifth time I passed him, he waved and smiled at me and told me to keep it up. I noticed he had an accent and I asked him where he was from. He explained to me that he was from Haiti and that he had recently turned ninety. I was so moved that both of us had birthdays on practically the same day and we were both challenging ourselves on the same cruel hill. The man was fluent in Spanish, so we were able to have a nice conversation.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;These days I don&amp;rsquo;t run much. I do more work with weights and I also swim a little. Maybe I should put together a modest running schedule and see how faithfully I am able to stick to it. I miss the long hours I used to spend running along Union Turnpike and in Alley Pond Park.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I am not fast and have never been a fast runner. But, I still get lost in my own slow rhythm, and it&amp;rsquo;s easy for me to forget my problems under the sky, and in a big wooded park. I have so much clutter in my room and in my life! When I run, I feel totally free. Running keeps me simple.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Simplicity is something I have lost sight of recently. I mean, I was going through some boxes in my closet and I found some of my old notebooks, journals. I opened one of my old diaries, and found I had filled page after page with Guru&amp;rsquo;s aphorisms- inspiring poems from his &amp;ldquo;Christmas Trip&amp;rdquo; pilgrimages to various parts of the world. One poem I had copied out was:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;Life is short.&lt;br /&gt;
		Hope is long.&lt;br /&gt;
		Promise is vast.&lt;br /&gt;
		Promise-fulfillment is perfect perfection.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;&amp;mdash;Sri Chinmoy, &lt;em&gt;My Christmas-New Year-Vacation Aspiration-Prayers&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Maybe I should go back to copying out Guru&amp;rsquo;s short inspiring aphorisms!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I like how this poem contrasts the brevity of life with the length of hope and the vastness of promise.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Sometimes the spiritual life can seem repetitive. I know of Zen Buddhist monks who tend the same little garden every day for hours and hours to remind themselves that even the tiniest tasks deserve to be done with respect and devoted attention. Like that, I find that my spiritual life is composed of hundreds of little tasks. These include daily prayers and affirmations, keeping my room clean and organized (that&amp;rsquo;s an uphill battle to make the hill on 150th street look like a piece of cake!), doing spiritual reading, keeping a meditative journal (Inspiration-Letters has definitely helped me a lot with this) and exercising. Sometimes I make a checklist, and when I do everything on the list, I go out to the local ice cream shop and order a large bowl of frozen custard. As for the last item on the list, exercise, I often turn to Sri Chinmoy&amp;rsquo;s poems for the final burst of inspiration I need.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;One old poem I like a lot is this one:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
	&lt;h4&gt;
		In Supreme Gratitude&lt;/h4&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;Lord,&lt;br /&gt;
		I wish to shine&lt;br /&gt;
		In supreme gratitude;&lt;br /&gt;
		Therefore&lt;br /&gt;
		I am awake,&lt;br /&gt;
		I am walking,&lt;br /&gt;
		I am running,&lt;br /&gt;
		Toward the golden Destination-dance.&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;&amp;mdash;Sri Chinmoy, excerpt of poem 392 from &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.srichinmoylibrary.com/books/0241/1/392/index.html&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;Transcendence-Perfection&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I like how, on Sri Chinmoy&amp;rsquo;s path, poetry, exercise, meditation and service to the world all go together. His is one of the rare integrated paths of yoga that is all-welcoming, all-affirming. In the poem I just quoted above, I like how the destination itself is a dance; it is not static. We wake up, walk, and run so that we can finally join in that mysterious dance that is the very cosmic rhythm of the universe. Save me a lawn chair for the next marathon. I might not run, but I will definitely cheer.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Welcome to the &lt;em&gt;Running Issue&lt;/em&gt;, dear friends!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mahiruha&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
